Privacy Nutrition Labels: A Browser Extension for Transparent Privacy Practices

Group 5
HCI Research Methods Course
[Date]

Group Members: [Names]


ABSTRACT

Privacy policies are notoriously difficult to read. Most people don't even try - studies show less than 10% of users actually read them before clicking "accept." We're designing a browser extension that fixes this problem by turning dense legal text into something that looks like a nutrition label on food packaging. Just like you can quickly see if your cereal has too much sugar, you'll be able to see if a website is collecting too much data.

Our extension displays an A-F grade for each website you visit, showing what data they collect, how they use it, who they share it with, and what rights you have. It also detects third-party trackers in real-time. To test whether this actually helps people, we're using three complementary research methods: having privacy experts evaluate the design (N=5), surveying regular users about their attitudes and behaviors (N=300), and watching people use the tool while they browse (N=8).

We expect to find that making privacy information visual and simple increases both understanding and awareness. More importantly, we want to see if it changes behavior - do people actually make different choices when privacy information is easy to access?

Keywords: privacy, browser extension, nutrition labels, transparency, tracking, user interface


